Chisholm [229] speculated that the maximum biomass and maximum growth rate could be related to cell nutrient requirements of microalgae. Using the diffusion limitation model of Morel et al. [230], she determined the nitrogen requirement for a spherical cell. The steady state, diffusion flux of nitrogen, with a nitrate concentration C to a cell of diameter, d, is given by J = 2πdDC, where D is the molecular diffusion coefficient of the nutrient (10−5 cm2 s−1). Chisholm noted that J ≥ μQN was necessary for a cell to grow, where QN is the cell quota of nitrogen in moles N cell−1. QN was determined from carbon content of the cell using the Redfield ratio of 16C:N for cells in exponential growth and the Strathmann’s equation to relate carbon content to cell volume, πd3/6. Recasting J in terms of μ, gives μ=2πdDCQN−1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
